<H3> <TI>   Double Disk Capacity Laser Diode Developed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Double Disk Capacity Laser Diode Developed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1406062694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0555 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1406062694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 14 KYODO -- Toshiba Corp. said Tuesday 
[14 Jun] it will begin global marketing of a new red-light 
semiconductor laser diode that significantly increases the 
storage capacity of optical disk systems. 
  The TOLD9151mb operates at a wavelength of 685 nanometers, 
compared with the 780 nanometers currently used in optical disk 
systems, Toshiba said. A nanometer is one-billionth of a meter. 
  The smaller spot size allows almost double the volume of 
information to be stored on the same size disk, it said. 
  Mass production of the device, at some 60,000 units per 
month, will begin at the end of the year. Toshiba has begun 
shipping samples of the laser diode at a price of 15,000 yen per 
unit. 

</TEXT>

