<LP>
   British scientists reported progress in understanding an
unexpected discovery about silicon that researchers hope may
be a breakthrough in electronics materials.
   The discovery, reported a year ago, is that an old,
little-used form of silicon, called porous silicon, can be
made to glow. If exploited, scientists hope that the
discovery will someday make cheap silicon usable for making
lasers and electronic displays that are currently made from
such expensive, difficult-to-fabricate materials as gallium
arsenide. Light-emitting silicon chips might also be the
basis of super-fast optical computers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In this week's issue of the journal Nature, British
scientist L.T. Canham and a colleague, A.G. Cullis, report
new experiments in which they've increased the intensity of
the light glow coming from silicon and gained some clues as
to why the light emission may be peculiar to porous silicon.
   Like many materials, silicon can absorb energy and re-emit
it as light. But the silicon ordinarily used in electronics
re-emits only a weak beam of invisible infrared light, which
is one reason why silicon has a dull, gray or black
appearance rather than the sheen of many metals.
   Porous silicon is a thin film of silicon that has been
electrochemically etched. The silicon film doesn't etch
uniformly, so it is riddled with tiny pores and channels.
   In their report, Messrs. Canham and Cullis say they gained
new evidence that the light emission in porous silicon stems
from a so-called quantum size effect, that is, an effect
related to the size of the etched channels. They etched four
samples of porous silicon, each with a different width of
pores and channels. Of the four samples, the most intense
light beam -- a bright red glow -- came from porous silicon
with the narrowest channels. Narrowest in their terms is
about three nanometers; a nanometer is about four
100-millionths of an inch.
   The researchers say that if they can understand why porous
silicon glows they may be able to answer a much bigger
question -- whether light emission from porous silicon can be
stimulated by an electric current. So far, the experiments
have used only beams of laser light to induce the silicon to
glow. Electronic devices such as communications lasers or
light-emitting diodes or even futuristic computer chips
employing light signals are useful largely because they
convert electrical signals to light signals and vice versa.
</TEXT>
