UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   Scientists at American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.'s Bell
Laboratories said they have developed the world's smallest
semiconductor lasers.
   AT&amp;T said the lasers are so tiny (about five microns in
diameter) that at least 10,000 would fit on the head of a
pin. AT&amp;T and its rivals have been racing to boost
transmission power of fiber-optic communications equipment
and to miniaturize devices that comprise such gear to reduce
cost and make them easier to service.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "This is a very novel semiconductor laser structure," said
Erich Ippen, a Massachusetts Institute of Technology
professor who specializes in lasers and optics. "The use of
high-density microscopic lasers as interconnects is
potentially quite important" for linking information systems
in the future, he said.
   AT&amp;T is looking at using "these beautiful little
structures" as communications devices for optical switches
and connectors for linking computers and the devices within
them, said Richart Slusher, chief of Bell Labs' Optical
Physics Research department, Murray Hill, N.J. However, AT&amp;T
scientists must first show that the new devices can be made
as inexpensively as current electrical connectors and that
they are compatible with silicon-based electronic equipment,
he added.
   Pictures supplied by AT&amp;T show the microscopic devices,
dubbed "microdisk lasers," look like thumbtacks when viewed
through a scanning electron microscope. The head of each one
of these "tacks" is 400 atoms thick, or one-thousandth the
diameter of a human hair. Dr. Slusher said the devices are
Bell Labs' "biggest breakthrough" since so-called
surface-emitting lasers were developed about three years ago.
Such lasers use two microscopic mirrors to concentrate a
light beam on the laser chip's interior surface before
shooting the beam in the form of a cone.
   The new lasers were designed by Bell Labs' researcher Sam
McCall to operate in the so-called "whispering gallery" mode,
named for the sound effect associated with St. Paul's
Cathedral in London, where a person can whisper and be heard
clearly along the wall of the dome. In a similar fashion, Dr.
McCall's lasers are said to shoot their light pulses or
photons along the edge of the disk-shaped laser, or the path
of least resistance, AT&amp;T said.
   Each laser, which is crafted of indium gallium arsenide
"sandwiched" between indium gallium arsenide phosphide, took
about nine months to develop, said Dr. Slusher, who noted
that Dr. McCall worked on the team that developed AT&amp;T's
surface-emitting devices.
</TEXT>
