<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: AP File Photograph; IBM last year showed off its power over the
atom by positioning 35 xenon atoms to spell out its corporate logo.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  SCIENCE; TECHNOLOGY; RESEARCH  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  SCIENTISTS are beginning to gain the ability to manipulate matter by its most
basic components -- molecule by molecule and even atom by atom.;   That
ability, while now very crude, might one day allow people to build almost
unimaginably small electronic circuits and machines, producing, for example, a
supercomputer invisible to the naked eye.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Science &amp; Medicine  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HARNESSING THE ATOM: SCIENTISTS THINK SMALL  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Nanotechnology  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Some futurists even imagine building tiny robots that could travel through
the body performing surgery on damaged cells.;   Such molecular-level
computers and robots are decades away and might never be practical. Even so,
molecular manufacturing promises to lead to great advances in electronic
devices, new materials of all sorts and the understanding of nature.;   "The
ability to manipulate and to observe and measure things on that scale is
tremendously exciting," said Dr. John Armstrong, chief scientist at the
International Business Machines Corp. "We will have the ability to make
electronic and mechanical devices atom by atom," he said, emphasizing his
belief that only critical parts of circuits, not entire computers, could be
built this way because of the complexity involved.;   IBM, in fact, became one
of the first companies to demonstrate precise control over atoms last year
when it positioned 35 atoms of the element xenon to spell out its corporate
logo.;   The emerging field, which draws on advances in physics, chemistry, 
biology and computer science, is called nanotechnology because the structures
being built would be measured in nanometers, or billionths of a meter. A
nanometer is about the size of three atoms.;   Today's finest microelectronic
circuits have features about one micron wide, or a millionth of a meter.
That's about 1 percent of the diameter of a human hair.;   Researchers in a
field known as micromechanics have built gears, motors and other mechanical
devices that are measured in the tens or hundreds of microns and are so small
they can be accidentally inhaled. But nanometer-scale devices would be smaller
still, one-thousandth their size.;   Today's microelectronic circuits rely on
billions of electrons flowing from place to place. A nanotechnology circuit,
by contrast, might differentiate between a zero and a one by a single molecule
changing its position or its shape.;   Today's chemistry is done, essentially,
by putting the ingredients in a test tube or vat, heating and shaking, and
relying on the random motion of atoms to form the desired compounds.;   "It's
like trying to assemble a radio by putting the components in a bag and
shaking," said Dr. Ralph Merkle, a scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research
Center who is working on nanotechnology.;   It works well for simple
compounds, he said, but it would be hard to imagine ever building a
molecular-sized robot this way.;   So some scientists believe the true
revolution will come by precisely snapping atoms and molecules into place,
sort of a miniature version of the way radios and other products are built.
This idea is called molecular nanotechnology or molecular manufacturing.;  
"Nanotechnology is a very fancy buzzword for the chemistry of the next
century," said Dr. Nadrian Seeman, a professor of chemistry at New York
University. "To a certain extent, we're going to emulate the way things are
done in cells.";   Until now, nanotechnology, particularly molecular
nanotechnology, has been less a science than the vision of one man, Dr. K.
Eric Drexler, a 36-year-old visiting scholar at Stanford University.;  
Drexler, who fashioned his own Ph.D. program in nanotechnology at MIT, has
outlined his ideas in two books, "Engines of Creation" (Anchor
Press/Doubleday) in 1986 and this year's "Unbounding the Future" (William
Morrow &amp; Co.), written with Chris Peterson and Gayle Pergamit.;   Drexler and
Peterson, his wife, formed the Foresight Institute, a non-profit organization
in Palo Alto, which sponsored a nanotechnology conference here this month that
drew about 150 researchers.;   Drexler predicts that tiny machines controlled
by nanocomputers and powered by nanomotors will one day swim through the blood
vessels fighting viruses, or grab chlorine atoms out of the sky to protect the
ozone layer.  </TEXT>
