</CO>
<MS>
TECHNOLOGY (TEC)
</MS>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<RE>
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
NEW YORK (NY)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   Researchers at International Business Machines Corp. have
plucked individual silicon atoms from a surface and placed
them in precise locations, raising the possibility of
electronic devices that could be built an atom at a time.
   The feat, reported in today's issue of Science, a weekly
journal, follows a demonstration last year in which IBM
scientists pulled individual atoms of xenon gas around to
form patterns, such as the company's famous logo, on a metal
surface.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   While both demonstrations used the same tool, an
IBM-invented microscope, to manipulate atoms in precise ways,
IBM said the new silicon technique was particularly relevant
to its dream of building electronic circuits with parts that
measure only one atom or one molecule across.
   By comparison, the circuitry in today's top-performance
computer chips is measured in microns, or millionths of a
meter -- at least 1,000 times coarser than atomic-scale
devices, which would be measured in nanometers, or billionths
of a meter. In theory, smaller circuitry permits faster, less
expensive and more complex computing.
   A scientist at American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.'s Bell
Laboratories cautioned, however, that such advances remain
far in the future. "This is a fine piece of work, but it's
just one step further along the road," said researcher
Russell Becker, who has demonstrated a similar but
less-reliable technique with germanium atoms. "No one should
think that they'll be making {electronic devices} this way
next year."
   Indeed, much remains to be figured out, including
mass-production techniques and even the form of the miniature
parts themselves. At such tiny scales, electric particles
obey the esoteric rules of quantum physics, meaning that
conventional transistors can't easily be used. Instead,
scientists are noodling around with different types of new
devices, which go by names such as quantum wells and quantum
dots.
   In addition to electronic applications, IBM said its new
method could point the way toward modifying existing
molecules by shunting their component atoms around, or even
make it possible to build customized molecules, atom by atom.
Since the method isn't limited to silicon, these capabilities
might be useful in pharmaceutical and genetics research,
which currently use different ways to customize molecules.
   IBM, based in Armonk, N.Y., said its latest demonstration
was important because it showed that the so-called scanning
tunneling microscope, or STM, can be used to break atoms free
of strong chemical bonds to other atoms -- not just to pull
around atoms of "noble" elements such as xenon, which
interact very weakly with their surroundings.
   The STM, for whose invention two IBM scientists shared a
Nobel Prize in 1987, is normally used in physics and
materials laboratories to produce images of individual atoms
and molecules. The microscope has a very slender tungsten tip
that, when energized by a tiny electric current, can trace
the atomic surface contours of many materials.
   Researchers at IBM and elsewhere have recently discovered,
however, that the tip can also manipulate other atoms by
picking them up, dropping them and dragging them. In an
interview, IBM scientist Phaedron Avouris, one of the authors
of the Science report, compared the STM tip to "a primitive
robotic arm."
   In the latest experiment, a combination of electrical and
chemical forces allows the tip to wrench silicon atoms away
from their brethren on a solid surface. The tip is then
moved, and the atoms are dumped at a predetermined location.
"Since we have to yank atoms out of the solid, the amount of
control is not so high" as in the xenon experiments, conceded
Mr. Avouris, who said the entire process took only a fraction
of a second.
   On the other hand, he noted, his demonstration had
immediate relevance because it used silicon, the building
block of today's electronic devices, rather than xenon.
"Obviously, we had microelectronic applications in mind," he
said.
   The latest demonstration was done in IBM's laboratory in
Yorktown Heights, N.Y., while the earlier work with xenon was
done independently in an IBM lab in San Jose, Calif.
</TEXT>
