   IBM Scientists
   Create a Switch
   With One Atom
   ----
   By Laurence Hooper
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/15/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   IBM
</CO>
<MS>
INDUSTRIAL (IDU)
TECHNOLOGY (TEC)
</MS>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
ELECTRICAL COMPONENTS AND EQUIPMENT (ELQ)
SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)
</IN>
<RE>
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
NEW YORK (NY)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Researchers at International Business Machines
Corp. have demonstrated a tiny switch that depends on the
motion of a single atom, making it the smallest electronic
device in existence.
   While any practical application is likely to be more than
a decade away, the advance shows that such minuscule devices
aren't beyond the reach of current technology. Coupled with
other recent breakthroughs, the new "atom switch" raises the
possibility that electronic circuits may someday be built
with parts measuring only an atom or molecule across.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   By comparison, the circuitry in today's top-performance
computer chips is measured in microns, or millionths of a
meter, at least 1,000 times coarser than atomic-scale
devices, which would be measured in nanometers, or billionths
of a meter. In theory, smaller circuitry permits faster,
less-expensive and more-complex computing.
   The technological feat, reported in today's issue of
Nature, a British science journal, is the latest trick to be
performed by an IBM-invented tool known as the scanning
tunneling microscope. The STM, for which two IBM scientists
shared a Nobel Prize in 1987, was initially used to produce
images of individual atoms and molecules, but it's emerging
as an all-purpose instrument for manipulating individual
atoms with startling precision.
   Scientists at IBM and elsewhere have previously used the
STM to move around atoms on a surface to form patterns such
as the IBM logo, as well as to pluck atoms from a surface and
deposit them elsewhere, much like a robotic arm. The
microscope has a very slender tungsten tip that, when
energized by a tiny electric current, can trace and
manipulate the atomic surface contours of many materials.
   Donald Eigler, one of the authors of the Nature report,
said in an interview that the new switch builds on previous
STM research done at his lab in San Jose, Calif., including
the IBM logo stunt last year. Working at an extremely low
temperature, he has been using the STM to move atoms of xenon
around on a nickel surface.
   Mr. Eigler said he and his colleagues recognized almost
immediately that they might make a switch using the STM but
were stymied by the thought that it should look something
like a transistor, the building block of today's electronic
circuits.
   Finally, he said, they realized that a much simpler device
might be made that would merely shuttle a xenon atom back and
forth between the STM's tip and the metal surface. "Once that
idea got through my thick skull, the principle took only a
half-day or a day's work to demonstrate," he said. "It was
quite simple."
   When the xenon atom is on the tip of the STM, more
electrical current flows between the tip and the surface than
when the atom is on the surface. That gives the switch "on"
and "off" positions that can be used to transmit or store
digital information, the language of ones and zeros that
makes computers tick.
   "There are very few times in the life of a scientist when
he realizes that he's seeing something that no one has ever
seen," said Mr. Eigler of the first time he saw the switch
working. "That's the highest high there is for a scientist,
and this was one of those moments for me. It's the stuff that
keeps scientists going," said Mr. Eigler, who spoke from
Switzerland, where he is attending a conference to mark the
10th anniversary of the STM's invention. He said he's giving
a presentation on his atom switch tomorrow.
   Of course, huge obstacles remain -- not least the fact
that Mr. Eigler's tiny switch needs a vacuum around it,
operates at extremely low temperatures and has an expensive
STM attached, making it impractical as an everyday electronic
device. In a related article in Nature, Stanford University
scientist C.F. Quate notes that even if many problems were
solved, using Mr. Eigler's atom switches to store information
would still be prohibitively slow.
   To overcome the speed barrier, Mr. Quate calls for
research into "massively parallel" systems that could operate
many atom switches at a time. He holds out the tantalizing
possibility that the contents of the Library of Congress
might one day be stored on a 12-inch disk.
   Mr. Eigler endorsed the idea of parallel systems but also
suggested that some molecules may already exist that could
act as the kind of switch he has demonstrated, making
possible mass-production of "buckets" of atom switches. "Of
course, the truth is that we don't know whether this
technology will be stillborn or not," Mr. Eigler said. "But
the only way to find out is to go after it."
</TEXT>
